From the code you provided it seems that you are trying to use verify.twilio.com as a proxy server. The [verify.twilio.com][1] is an end-point for a Twilio service to verify end-users which is not needed to send SMS. 

If you are trying to create a custom TwilioRestClient, here is a code sample from  the Twilio #C SDK for a custom [TwilioRestClient][2]:

    public static class ProxiedTwilioClientCreator
        {
            private static HttpClient _httpClient;
    
            private static void CreateHttpClient()
            {
                var proxyUrl = ConfigurationManager.AppSettings[&quot;ProxyServerUrl&quot;];
                var handler = new HttpClientHandler()
                {
                    Proxy = new WebProxy(proxyUrl),
                    UseProxy = true
                };
    
                _httpClient = new HttpClient(handler);
                var byteArray = Encoding.Unicode.GetBytes(
                    ConfigurationManager.AppSettings[&quot;ProxyUsername&quot;]
                        + &quot;:&quot;
                        + ConfigurationManager.AppSettings[&quot;ProxyPassword&quot;]
                );
    
                _httpClient.DefaultRequestHeaders.Authorization =
                    new System.Net.Http.Headers.AuthenticationHeaderValue(
                        &quot;Basic&quot;,
                        Convert.ToBase64String(byteArray)
                    );
            }
    
            public static TwilioRestClient GetClient()
            {
                var accountSid = ConfigurationManager.AppSettings[&quot;TwilioAccountSid&quot;];
                var authToken = ConfigurationManager.AppSettings[&quot;TwilioAuthToken&quot;];
    
                if (_httpClient == null)
                {                    
                    CreateHttpClient();
                }
    
                var twilioRestClient = new TwilioRestClient(
                    accountSid,
                    authToken,
                    httpClient: new Twilio.Http.SystemNetHttpClient(_httpClient)
                );
    
                return twilioRestClient;
            }
        }

The proxy server will make it appear to your client applications that you are sending from a different non-Twilio url. However, if you are using a server based app such as ASP.NET or Blazor Server then your client application won&#39;t have access to the url so no real need to do this. Twilio explains this further in a blob post on [&quot;Protect Your Identify with Proxy Servers, Twilio, and C#&quot;][3].


  [1]: https://www.twilio.com/docs/verify
  [2]: https://github.com/twilio/twilio-csharp/blob/main/advanced-examples/custom-http-client.md
  [3]: https://www.twilio.com/blog/protect-your-identity-with-proxy-servers-twilio-and-c-html

